((* set suite_intro = {
  "performance": "This suite measures raw forwarding capacity --- how many packets per second the UPF moves --- across a range of Ethernet frame sizes (given in bytes). For each size it reports the \\textbf{NDR} (No-Drop Rate: the highest offered rate with zero packet loss) and the \\textbf{PDR} (Partial-Drop Rate: the highest rate with at most 0.1\\% loss), in millions of packets per second (Mpps). Frame size matters because a UPF does almost the same work on every packet regardless of its size: small frames (64--256\\,B) pack the most packets into a given bit-rate and are therefore the hardest, truest test of forwarding capacity, while large frames (1024--1518\\,B) resemble everyday user traffic and show the practical ceiling. For worst-case capacity, the small-frame row is the one to watch.",
  "load": "This suite measures behaviour under many simultaneous users, where each user is one PFCP \\emph{session} (its own forwarding rules). It records how many sessions the UPF will hold at once and, with a realistic number of users active together, confirms that every individual user's traffic is actually carried --- not merely the combined total.",
  "pfcp": "This suite checks the N4/PFCP control interface against 3GPP TS\\,29.244 --- the language the core uses to tell the UPF to set up, modify, delete, and error-handle user sessions. These are pass/fail conformance checks rather than performance numbers; all five should pass for a standards-compliant UPF."
} *))

